      Programming note: Money Stuff will be off tomorrow, back on Tuesday.E=
xxonLet=E2=80=99s say you are the chief executive officer of Exxon Mobil Co=
rp., and your second-biggest shareholder, BlackRock Inc., comes in for a me=
eting. =E2=80=9CWe would like you to drill less oil, spend more time on ren=
ewable energy and commit to being carbon-neutral by 2050,=E2=80=9D the Blac=
kRock team says. =E2=80=9CAbsolutely not, get out of my office,=E2=80=9D yo=
u say. What can BlackRock do about it?Actually let=E2=80=99s sharpen the hy=
pothetical a bit. BlackRock owns about 6.6% of Exxon=E2=80=99s stock. Let=
=E2=80=99s say that you, the Exxon CEO, had a meeting with the Vanguard Gro=
up right before your BlackRock meeting, and another one with State Street C=
orp. right after, and they say the exact same things as BlackRock. Combined=
, those three own=C2=A0about 20% of your stock. Let=E2=80=99s say you had m=
eetings with a few=C2=A0dozen other shareholders who also say the same thin=
gs, and in total they=C2=A0add up to 50.1% of your stock. They all want you=
 to drill less oil and do more renewables and commit to carbon neutrality, =
and you laugh at all of them and throw them out of your office. What can th=
ey do?Of course they can call up the board of directors of Exxon, your boss=
es, and say =E2=80=9Cfire this guy, he=E2=80=99s being mean to shareholders=
,=E2=80=9D but let us assume for this hypothetical that the board is aligne=
d with you and will do what you want rather than what shareholders want. Wh=
at else can they do?Well, they can do lots of things. Let=E2=80=99s list so=
me:=09They can put out press releases saying that you are bad, which is emb=
arrassing for you though it does not actually force your hand.=09They can v=
ote for   nonbinding shareholder resolutions asking you to prepare reports =
on your climate impact, which is also embarrassing for you. But you don=E2=
=80=99t technically have to do the report even if the shareholders vote for=
 it (the proposal is nonbinding), and even if you do the report that doesn=
=E2=80=99t mean you have to change your strategy.=09Each year you ask them =
to  approve your pay package and the pay of your other senior executives, a=
nd they could vote no. If they vote no, that will also be embarrassing for =
you, though technically the vote is nonbinding and you still get paid.=09Ea=
ch year your board of directors is up for election, and they could vote aga=
inst the directors. This perhaps sounds more important than it is, because =
the directors generally run unopposed. If they get a majority of the votes =
cast, they are re-elected. If a majority of shares are voted against a dire=
ctor, then, under Exxon=E2=80=99s  corporate governance guidelines, that di=
rector is  required to submit a resignation letter to the rest of the board=
. =E2=80=9CWithin 90 days after certification of the election results, the =
Board of Directors will decide, through a process managed by the Board Affa=
irs Committee and excluding the nominee in question, whether to accept the =
resignation. Absent a compelling reason for the director to remain on the B=
oard, the Board shall accept the resignation.=E2=80=9D So if a majority of =
shareholders vote against the directors, they probably=C2=A0should=C2=A0lea=
ve the board, but they don=E2=80=99t strictly have to. If a majority of sha=
reholders votes against all the directors then presumably the directors cou=
ld just decide not to accept each other=E2=80=99s resignations.=C2=A0=09Exx=
on=E2=80=99s directors and senior executives might be, or want to be, on th=
e boards of directors of=C2=A0other=C2=A0companies. BlackRock et al. are al=
so big shareholders of those other companies, and they might vote against t=
he Exxon people on their other boards, and that might lead to the Exxon peo=
ple losing some cushy directorships.I am sure I am missing some. None of th=
ese things are trivial. They are very important! Most big corporate CEOs wa=
nt to be liked=C2=A0and respected. (The previous=C2=A0CEO of Exxon went on =
to become the U.S. secretary of state!) They want to think that they=E2=80=
=99re doing a good job and creating shareholder value; they don=E2=80=99t w=
ant all their shareholders to be mad at them. They are members of corporate=
 and philanthropic boards=C2=A0and golf clubs=C2=A0with other executives an=
d investors, and they want to be respected by their peers.=C2=A0These symbo=
lic indications of investor displeasure matter a lot to almost all public c=
ompanies, and they=C2=A0give BlackRock and other big shareholders enormous =
influence. We  talk  about this  influence all the time. People=C2=A0worry=
=C2=A0about it all the time; they worry that these big shareholders have=C2=
=A0too much=C2=A0power over all of the companies.=C2=A0Still none of these =
things are exactly =E2=80=9Cthe shareholders can fire you,=E2=80=9D are the=
y?Another thing that the shareholders can do is[1]:=09They can sell their s=
tock: =E2=80=9CThis CEO doesn=E2=80=99t listen to us and isn=E2=80=99t doin=
g what we want, so we don=E2=80=99t want to own Exxon anymore.=E2=80=9D If =
enough of them sell their stock then the price of the stock will go down. T=
his is embarrassing for you =E2=80=94=C2=A0you want to think you=E2=80=99re=
 doing a good job and creating shareholder value, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but i=
t also affects you economically, because you own a bunch of Exxon stock per=
sonally and get paid in Exxon stock and options and so when the stock goes =
down you are less rich.[2]=C2=A0That is an important incentive, but it is m=
itigated here because your biggest shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0Vanguard and=
 BlackRock and State Street =E2=80=94=C2=A0run a lot of index money and=C2=
=A0can=E2=80=99t sell the stock. You are in the index, they have to own the=
 index, they have to own you. This is not really a threat they can make.Oka=
y now let=E2=80=99s do the big ones. What is the endgame? How do the shareh=
olders go from expressing displeasure to firing the CEO?There are two class=
ic answers, two binding=C2=A0ways for shareholders to fire the CEO. One is =
a hostile takeover. Some corporate raider, strategic rival=C2=A0or sharp-el=
bowed private equity firm notices the stock-price decline and dissatisfied =
shareholders and says =E2=80=9Chey I could buy this company cheap, do what =
the market wants it to do, and make a profit.=E2=80=9D The raider offers a =
premium to the current price (which is depressed due to shareholder dissati=
sfaction), the disgusted shareholders happily sell to the raider, the raide=
r fires the board and CEO and makes the changes that the shareholders were =
calling for.[3] This is sometimes called =E2=80=9Cthe market for corporate =
control,=E2=80=9D and it is in general the main reason for corporate CEOs t=
o worry about losing their jobs if their shareholders are unhappy.In genera=
l. In our particular hypothetical, though, Exxon happens to be a $250 billi=
on oil company. No one is going to do a hostile takeover of Exxon. This is =
not a very compelling threat for a giant company.The other classic answer i=
s a=C2=A0proxy fight. Some activist hedge fund (or corporate raider) notice=
s the stock-price decline and dissatisfied shareholders and says =E2=80=9Ch=
ey I could buy like 8% of this company cheap, force it to do what the marke=
t wants it to do, and make a profit.=E2=80=9D The activist buys stock, nomi=
