ootnote because, in most cases, large U.S. public companies  do not actuall=
y fund their projects by selling stock.=C2=A0[3] Or doesn=E2=80=99t: The ra=
ider owns the company now and does whatever she wants. But presumably this =
is all easier to do if the shareholders are *right* and there is some sort =
of value-add strategic change that the company could make. Also the raider =
might *be* one of the existing, disgusted shareholders, or might get financ=
ing from them.[4] The ideal is =E2=80=9Cas much as possible while staying s=
afely below 10%=E2=80=9D; bad things happen under U.S. securities law if yo=
u go above 10%.[5] An obvious response would be for BlackRock to say =E2=80=
=9Cfine, we=E2=80=99ll do the proxy fight ourselves,=E2=80=9D but they don=
=E2=80=99t really do that. It=E2=80=99s not really a specialization of the =
big asset managers, and it would probably get them a lot of negative attent=
ion from other companies.[6] There=E2=80=99s some indication that the share=
holders  think that=E2=80=99s what happened: =E2=80=9CExxon=E2=80=99s failu=
re to act on previous investor demands to tackle climate change led to the =
company=E2=80=99s loss, said New York Comptroller Thomas DiNapoli. =E2=80=
=98The fact that Exxon hasn=E2=80=99t been responsive up until now, in a wa=
y they set the stage for their own defeat,=E2=80=99 he said Wednesday in a =
Bloomberg TV interview.=E2=80=9D And in its explanation of its votes, Black=
Rock notes that it voted for Woods and Exxon=E2=80=99s lead independent dir=
ector to keep their board seats =E2=80=9Cbecause our engagement with each o=
f them over the past several months has given us greater confidence that th=
ey are prepared to internalize shareholder feedback=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0suggesting that, prior to the past several months (the proxy fight), the=
y weren=E2=80=99t.
