10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Tuesday.</em></p><h2 style=3D"font-weigh=
t: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif=
; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: =
0;">Exxon</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s say you are the ch=
ief executive officer of Exxon Mobil Corp., and your second-biggest shareho=
lder, BlackRock Inc., comes in for a meeting. =E2=80=9CWe would like you to=
 drill less oil, spend more time on renewable energy and <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23981726.277957/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3Nq=
LmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9leHhvbi12cy1hY3RpdmlzdHMtYmF0dGxlLW92ZXItZnV0dXJlLW9mLW9=
pbC1hbmQtZ2FzLXJlYWNoZXMtc2hvd2Rvd24tMTE2MjE5NTA5Njc_bW9kPWhwX2xlYWRfcG9zNw=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9beae1fc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">commit to being carbon-neutral by 2050</a>,=E2=80=
=9D the BlackRock team says. =E2=80=9CAbsolutely not, get out of my office,=
=E2=80=9D you say. What can BlackRock do about it?</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Actually let=E2=80=99s sharpen the hypothetical a bit. BlackRock ow=
ns about 6.6% of Exxon=E2=80=99s stock. Let=E2=80=99s say that you, the Exx=
on CEO, had a meeting with the Vanguard Group right before your BlackRock m=
eeting, and another one with State Street Corp. right after, and they say t=
he exact same things as BlackRock. Combined, those three own=C2=A0about 20%=
 of your stock. Let=E2=80=99s say you had meetings with a few=C2=A0dozen ot=
her shareholders who also say the same things, and in total they=C2=A0add u=
p to 50.1% of your stock. They all want you to drill less oil and do more r=
enewables and commit to carbon neutrality, and you laugh at all of them and=
 throw them out of your office. What can they do?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Of course they can call up the board of directors of Exxon, your bos=
ses, and say =E2=80=9Cfire this guy, he=E2=80=99s being mean to shareholder=
s,=E2=80=9D but let us assume for this hypothetical that the board is align=
ed with you and will do what you want rather than what shareholders want. W=
hat else can they do?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, they can do lot=
s of things. Let=E2=80=99s list some:</p><ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc=
; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>They can put out press releases saying that you are bad, which is embarras=
sing for you though it does not actually force your hand.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They can vote for <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/23981726.277957/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMjYvZXh4b24taGFzLWEtdG91Z2gtZ3JlZW4tYWN0a=
XZpc3Q/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9c1e060f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">  nonbinding shareholder resolutions</a> a=
sking you to prepare reports on your climate impact, which is also embarras=
sing for you. But you don=E2=80=99t technically have to do the report even =
if the shareholders vote for it (the proposal is nonbinding), and even if y=
ou do the report that doesn=E2=80=99t mean you have to change your strategy=
.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Each year you ask them to <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23981726.277957/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzM0MDg4LzAwMDExOTMxMjUyMTA4MjE=
0MC9kOTQxNTlkZGVmYzE0YS5odG0jdG9jOTQxNTlfMTM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcfbf1=
735" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> appr=
ove your pay package</a> and the pay of your other senior executives, and t=
hey could vote no. If they vote no, that will also be embarrassing for you,=
 though technically the vote is nonbinding and you still get paid.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Each year your board of directors is up fo=
r election, and they could vote against the directors. This perhaps sounds =
more important than it is, because the directors generally run unopposed. I=
f they get a majority of the votes cast, they are re-elected. If a majority=
 of shares are voted <em>against </em>a director, then, under Exxon=E2=80=
=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23981726.2779=
57/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3Jwb3JhdGUuZXh4b25tb2JpbC5jb20vQWJvdXQtdXMvV2hvLXdlLWFyZS9D=
b3Jwb3JhdGUtZ292ZXJuYW5jZS9Db3Jwb3JhdGUtZ292ZXJuYW5jZS1ndWlkZWxpbmVzLWFuZC1=
hZGRpdGlvbmFsLXBvbGljaWVzI0NvcnBvcmF0ZUdvdmVybmFuY2VHdWlkZWxpbmVz/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB2f9c30a4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> corporate governance guidelines</a>, that director is <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23981726.277957/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzM0MDg4LzAwMDExOTMxMjUyMDEwM=
jIyNi9kODY5NDczZGRlZjE0YS5odG0jdG9jODY5NDczXzI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe4e=
6e6f3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" title=3D"page 6" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;"> required to submit a resignation letter</a> to the rest of t=
he board. =E2=80=9CWithin 90 days after certification of the election resul=
ts, the Board of Directors will decide, through a process managed by the Bo=
ard Affairs Committee and excluding the nominee in question, whether to acc=
ept the resignation. Absent a compelling reason for the director to remain =
on the Board, the Board shall accept the resignation.=E2=80=9D So if a majo=
rity of shareholders vote against the directors, they probably=C2=A0<em>sho=
uld=C2=A0</em>leave the board, but they don=E2=80=99t strictly have to. If =
a majority of shareholders votes against all the directors then presumably =
the directors could just decide not to accept each other=E2=80=99s resignat=
ions.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Exxon=E2=80=99s direct=
ors and senior executives might be, or want to be, on the boards of directo=
rs of=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>companies. BlackRock et al. are also big sha=
reholders of those other companies, and they might vote against the Exxon p=
eople on their other boards, and that might lead to the Exxon people losing=
 some cushy directorships.</li></ul><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am sure =
I am missing some. None of these things are trivial. They are very importan=
t! Most big corporate CEOs want to be liked=C2=A0and respected. (The previo=
us=C2=A0CEO of Exxon went on to become the U.S. secretary of state!) They w=
ant to think that they=E2=80=99re doing a good job and creating shareholder=
 value; they don=E2=80=99t want all their shareholders to be mad at them. T=
hey are members of corporate and philanthropic boards=C2=A0and golf clubs=
=C2=A0with other executives and investors, and they want to be respected by=
 their peers.=C2=A0These symbolic indications of investor displeasure matte=
r a lot to almost all public companies, and they=C2=A0give BlackRock and ot=
her big shareholders enormous influence. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/23981726.277957/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDktMTMvdGhlLWNyaXNpcy13YXMtaW4tdGhlLXN5c3Rl=
bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd11e34f2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: soli=
d; background-color: #ccc;"> talk</a> <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/23981726.277957/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMjQvdGhlLXZhY2NpbmUtaXMtbm90LWEtY29tcGV0aXRpb2=
4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB13dfcc23" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> about</a> this <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/23981726.277957/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMTItMDcvcmVndWxhdG9ycy1hc2staWYtaW5kZXgtZnVuZ=
HMtYXJlLWJhZA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBeaae4e6d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> influence</a> all the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23981726.277957/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDEtMDkvcGVvcGxlLWFyZS13b3=
JyaWVkLWFib3V0LWluZGV4LWZ1bmRz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB431c181a" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">time</a>. People=
=C2=A0<em>worry=C2=A0</em>about it all the time; they worry that these big =
shareholders have=C2=A0<em>too much=C2=A0</em>power over all of the compani=
es.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still none of these things are ex=
actly =E2=80=9Cthe shareholders can fire you,=E2=80=9D are they?</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another thing that the shareholders can do is[1]:</p>=
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They can sell their stock: =E2=80=9CTh=
is CEO doesn=E2=80=99t listen to us and isn=E2=80=99t doing what we want, s=
o we don=E2=80=99t want to own Exxon anymore.=E2=80=9D If enough of them se=
ll their stock then the price of the stock will go down. This is embarrassi=
ng for you =E2=80=94=C2=A0you want to think you=E2=80=99re doing a good job=
 and creating shareholder value, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it also affects yo=
u economically, because you own a bunch of Exxon stock personally and get p=
aid in Exxon stock and options and so when the stock goes down you are less=
 rich.[2]=C2=A0</li></ul><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is an important =
incentive, but it is mitigated here because your biggest shareholders =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0Vanguard and BlackRock and State Street =E2=80=94=C2=A0run a lo=
t of index money and=C2=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t sell the stock</em>. You are in=
 the index, they have to own the index, they have to own you. This is not r=
eally a threat they can make.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Okay now let=
=E2=80=99s do the big ones. What is the endgame? How do the shareholders go=
 from expressing displeasure to firing the CEO?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">There are two classic answers, two <em>binding=C2=A0</em>ways for shar=
eholders to fire the CEO. One is a <em>hostile takeover</em>. Some corporat=
e raider, strategic rival=C2=A0or sharp-elbowed private equity firm notices=
 the stock-price decline and dissatisfied shareholders and says =E2=80=9Che=
y I could buy this company cheap, do what the market wants it to do, and ma=
ke a profit.=E2=80=9D The raider offers a premium to the current price (whi=
ch is depressed due to shareholder dissatisfaction), the disgusted sharehol=
ders happily sell to the raider, the raider fires the board and CEO and mak=
es the changes that the shareholders were calling for.[3] This is sometimes=
 called =E2=80=9Cthe market for corporate control,=E2=80=9D and it is in ge=
neral the main reason for corporate CEOs to worry about losing their jobs i=
f their shareholders are unhappy.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In genera=
l. In our particular hypothetical, though, Exxon happens to be a $250 billi=
on oil company. No one is going to do a hostile takeover of Exxon. This is =
not a very compelling threat for a giant company.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">The other classic answer is a=C2=A0<em>proxy fight</em>. Some activi=
st hedge fund (or corporate raider) notices the stock-price decline and dis=
satisfied shareholders and says =E2=80=9Chey I could buy like 8% of this co=
mpany cheap, force it to do what the market wants it to do, and make a prof=
it.=E2=80=9D The activist buys stock, nominates directors and=C2=A0runs a p=
roxy fight to get them elected to the board. This is different from the usu=
al uncontested director elections and nonbinding shareholder proposals: In =
a proxy fight, the activist writes her own proxy statement, pays to send it=
 to shareholders, and spends a lot of time and money trying to get her nomi=
nees elected. If she wins =E2=80=94=C2=A0if her nominees get more votes tha=
n the company=E2=80=99s nominees =E2=80=94=C2=A0then she wins, for real.=C2=
=A0It=E2=80=99s not advisory or nonbinding or we-submit-a-resignation-lette=
r-and-think-about-it; it=E2=80=99s just the nominees who get more votes get=
 on the board.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are occasionally=
 proxy fights like this at giant companies. There are impediments, though. =
One problem is that classic activists like to buy a lot of stock; my 8% num=
ber above is a reasonable order of magnitude.[4] Contested proxy fights are=
 risky and expensive for the activist. Buying a lot of stock makes it more =
likely that the activist will win, because she gets to vote her own shares;=
 starting with 8% of the vote is better than starting with less. Also, thou=
gh, the activist is hoping that if she does win the stock will go up and sh=
e will make money. The more shares she owns, the more money she will make; =
also, if she owns more shares she will capture a greater=C2=A0<em>percentag=
e=C2=A0</em>of the value she adds. If her ideas add $1 billion of value to =
the company and she owns 8% of the stock, she will make $80 million. If she=
 owns 0.1% of the stock, she will make $1 million. A successful=C2=A0activi=
st with a large stake is creating a lot of value for herself; a successful =
activist with a small stake is creating value mostly for other people out o=
f, like, selfless philanthropy. You do not expect to see a ton of selfless =
philanthropy among activist hedge-fund managers.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Again, Exxon is a $250 billion company. If an activist wants to=
